A few thought about handling &quot;endless&quot; data and need-to-know-beforehand headers.
&lt;!-- language-all: lang-java --&gt;
1. Don&#39;t trip over by using `ByteBuffer` against its defined semantic.
```
// wrong or - at least - counter-intuitive
buffer.clear();
buffer.put...(...);
line.write(buffer.array(), 0, buffer.position());
```
It is meant to be used like this:
```
buffer.rewind();
buffer.put...(...);
buffer.flip();
line.write(buffer.array(), 0, buffer.remaining());
```
... although in this specific case there is no real benefit. `ByteBuffer#flip` is very important for `ByteBuffer#get...` methods, for example if you use NIO for writing to a file.

2. Simply write to a file **without** a RIFF/WAV header. Depending on your requirements, you could just serialize* your `AudioFormat` and save it in a different place (out-of-band), preferably as file metadata (uncommon but most often possible). This is possible because there is no complex multiplexing needed in your case.

* or keep your AudioFormat hardcoded even at file playback&#39;s side - not recommended.

```
try (var fileChannel = FileChannel.open(Path.of(&quot;test.pcm&quot;), StandardOpenOption.CREATE_NEW)) {
```

```
   buffer.flip();
   line.write(buffer.array(), 0, buffer.remaining());
   buffer.flip();
   fileChannel.write(buffer);
```
... or use a better suited container format.
```
}
```
3. The same data you read from `line` can also be read from a file. It&#39;s the exact same bitstream - the joys of digital data.

