Here&#39;s the source of the `hashCode` method :

    public int hashCode() {
        int h = hash;
        if (h == 0) {
            int off = offset;
            char val[] = value;
            int len = count;

            for (int i = 0; i &lt; len; i++) {
                h = 31*h + val[off++];
            }
            hash = h;
        }
        return h;
    }

You see that the value is computed only when you (first) call `hashCode`. Which doesn&#39;t matter as `hash` **is private** : you can only get it normally using the `hashCode` method.

To answer your explicit question : the hash of a string (as returned by `hashCode`) is `0` for empty strings (but [not only for empty strings](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/18746394/can-a-not-empty-string-have-a-hashcode-of-zero)).

